```

Called from `pyserver/services/notifications.py:21` (`send_task_notification`, the outbound webhook-delivery path).

**For comparison, the correct pattern already exists** in `webclient/src/http.ts`, `fetchWithRetry` (lines 18–36) — it should be mirrored:

```ts
const RETRYABLE = new Set([429, 502, 503, 504]);
...
const retryable = error instanceof HttpError && RETRYABLE.has(error.status);
if (!retryable && !(error instanceof TypeError)) {
  throw error;
}
```

## 2. Mechanism / fix

`urllib.error.HTTPError` is a subclass of `urllib.error.URLError`. `retry_request`'s `except (urllib.error.URLError, TimeoutError)` therefore catches *every* non-2xx HTTP response (400, 404, 422, …) the exact same way it catches a real transient failure (DNS error, connection refused, timeout) — there's no inspection of the status code at all. A `400 Bad Request` (malformed payload) gets retried `DEFAULT_ATTEMPTS` (3) times with backoff even though the response can never change on retry.

The frontend's `webclient/src/http.ts:fetchWithRetry` already got this right when it was written (it allowlists `{429, 502, 503, 504}` and rethrows everything else immediately), so this looks like the fix from that commit was applied to the browser client but never mirrored into the server-side outbound `HttpClient`.

**Fix:** in `pyserver/http_client.py`, catch `urllib.error.HTTPError` separately (before the general `URLError` handler), check `exc.code` against a retryable set (e.g. `{429, 502, 503, 504}`), and re-raise immediately for anything else; keep the broad `except (urllib.error.URLError, TimeoutError)` only for genuine network-level failures (which won't have a `.code`). No other call sites need to change — `notifications.py` just inherits whatever `HttpClient.retry_request` decides.

